ObjectStates.Name: CardCustom
ObjectStates.Description:
His name in means "Tainted Blood".  He doesn't care for his Betazoid half.  He despises his empathy, which he can't control.  In addition to surpressing any emotions he feels from those around him, he must supress his shame every time he's reminded he's half Betazoid.

He is largely unaccepted by other Vulcans, and Betazoids usually pity him so fiercely it's hard not to cry, so he avoids them.  So damn tragic.

ObjectStates.Name: Counter
ObjectStates.Description: In the official rules, the current total is kept secret from the players.  But this secrecy is instantly void if any of the players know the rules.  They will be able to tell when Threat increases and by how much.  Further, players new to the game are less likely to grasp how Threat works if the total is a secret.

ObjectStates.Name: CardCustom
ObjectStates.Description: Lt. Yox (surname first with Bajorans!) may look like Sito Jaxa, and act like Sito Jaxa, but she isn't.

ObjectStates.Name: CardCustom
ObjectStates.Description: He installed the implants himself; three of the more basic technologies found among the Borg wreckage following Wolf 359.  He was a Lt. Cmd. prior to this self-surgery he performed.  When Starfleet found out he'd done this without permission, he was demoted to Lieutenant.

ObjectStates.Name: CardCustom
ObjectStates.Description: First Cardassian in Starfleet.  Following the decimation of the Cardassian Union in the Dominion war, Cardassians everywhere were shamed.  Gatt is one Cardassian who found redeeming honor in Starfleet's example, and enlisted.

ObjectStates.Name: CardCustom
ObjectStates.Description:
So far this character is pretty much Janeway, whom I confess I don't like.  Since the GM often plays the Captain, it's most convenient if Cpt. Shadwell is generally unlikable so that she might be more naturally disregarded by the players.

Finding a reason for the Captain to be unavailable is easier than finding a reason for them to be on every away mission, or finding more activity for them during space battles. (commanders don't do much there)

ObjectStates.Name: Custom_Token
ObjectStates.Description:
There are 3 kinds of crewman: 

- Basic, unranked Starfleet crewmen.  These guys have no stats and are just background fodder.
- Supporting crew.  These are 'lower deck' officers.  You may choose up to 3 from this list to assist your team during an episode.
- Main characters, which are the bridge crew and doctor.

ObjectStates.Name: Custom_Token
ObjectStates.Description:
Steven "Woz" Wozniak invented both the modern concept of the personal computer and the personal computer itself using a 6502 processor.  Young Woz achieved in 1975 what the best engineers of the era had deemed impossible.

The 4-digit designation should really only be for TOS-era ships and ships with iterations.  So "6502" violates the rules as the world sees them, but so did Woz.

A snippet of dialogue from Odo in DS9 suggests Klingons can live over 150 years (unless Odo was joking).  But a snippet of dialogue from a klingon in Next Generation claims "there are no old warriors" when it comes to Klingons, suggesting the natural lifespan is rarely pushed.

ContainedObjects.Name: Custom_Token
ContainedObjects.Description: Born 2305 in France, believe it or not.  Successfully entered Starfleet in 2323.  Transferred to the helm of the Stargazer in 2333. ContainedObjects.Name: Custom_Token
ContainedObjects.Description:
In Voyager, Mark 1 is THE Doctor, Mark 2 is the hologram played by Andy Dick, Mark 3 is never referenced, and Dr. Zimmerman tells THE Doctor during a visit to the Alpha quadrant that they're currently on Mark 4.

In the Continuum campaign, Mark 3 was Z's attempt at having a medic with empathy from the getgo.

(continued in token GM notes)
ContainedObjects.GMNotes: Mark 3 took this programming too far.  She is extremely vain and is obsessed with learning what love feels like.  Not sex, she's not the slightest bit interested in that.  But the model inevitably falls for her patients, or thinks she does.  Dr. Z had her promptly replaced with Mark 4, but there's still some Mark 3 models on starships that haven't gotten the Mark 4 refit yet.

By the mid-2270s, Rand had been promoted to chief petty officer and transporter chief (Star Trek: The Motion Picture).  In 2286, she's a communications officer assigned to Starfleet Command on Earth (Star Trek IV).  By 2293, she is Lt. Jr. Grade aboard the USS Excelsior under Cpt Sulu (as seen in Star Trek VI and Voyager).

In 2269, he was promoted to commander, a rank he held for the next 25 years.  He also served as CMO aboard the Enterprise-A.  He's last seen at 137 years old, an admiral.

She served as the ship's historian before falling in love with Khan, mostly betraying her crew, and joining Khan in his exile on Ceti Alpha V.  Shortly after their exile she was killed by the planet's only native predator.

ContainedObjects.Name: Custom_Token

ContainedObjects.Name: Custom_Token
ContainedObjects.Description: Born January 6, 2230 in ShiKahr, Vulcan.  Commissioned as a Starfleet officer in 2250, and assigned to the USS Enterprise in 2254 under Captain Pike as science officer.  Once Kirk took over in 2265, Spock became first officer as well.  In 2284, Spock was promoted to Captain, though he did not captain a starship.  In 2293, he was the Federation's special envoy to the "Gorkon Initiative" (Star Trek VI).  In 2368, he went to Romulus.

0.title: PLR Notes
0.body:
- The easiest way to get good dice randomization is to drop them just under the Star Trek Continuum logo onto the big picture of the Woz.  They will slide down, usually catch the lip and spin before falling further to the table.


********  OPTIONAL 3D GRID  ***********
- MEASURING VERTICAL DISTANCE:  Each 2D plane is the top and bottom of a movement zone.  As with horizontal movement, vertical movement doesn't have to be defined beyond what zone your ship is in, so it works to just leave the tokens unlocked and resting on their plane level.

- MOVEMENT EXAMPLE:  If your token is on the 2nd level and you fly up to the 3rd level, that's 1-zone movement.  Measuring 3-dimensionally while imagining the zones are 8-sided 3d shapes would suck, so if you're flying up one plane level and left two zones, count that as 3-zone movement.

- EASIEST HORIZONTAL MOVEMENT:  Zoom the camera in between the planes.  Make sure your 'Lift Height' is low/off (interface at the top of your screen, man lifting weights).

- EASIEST VERTICAL MOVEMENT:  Press F8, select the token, and move it up/down.  Press F1 when done.

- The Top Down view mode (TTS has 3 view modes; this is NOT just angling the camera downwards) flattens the grid.  Good for a quick 2d view of the battlefield.

-- If you don't want the 3d grid, the easiest way to remove it is control-click each card and press delete.  A plane is made up of 16 cards, so control-clicking a bunch and pressing delete will save you time.  Then you can re-save your own version of the room without the 3d grid.
*******************************************

11.title: Encounter
11.body:
Setting:  Alpha Quadrant, June 3, 2385
(NextGen TV series ends 2371, Dominion War ended 2375, Voyager returned home 2378)


** Encounter at New France **


The Federation ship U.S.S. Gygax, stationed at the New France colony, has gone silent.  The colony has no starships to go up and investigate.  The Gygax drifts without power in slow orbit around New France.

The science vessel U.S.S. Woz, your team's ship, is the closest Federation ship to investigate.  If the Gygax is completely without power, it won't have life support and so time is a factor.

Upon arriving at New France, your crew may choose to try and contact the colony first.  If they do, the colony will be angry with them for wasting time talking to them.  Go save the Gygax!

As soon as the team has decided to approach the Gygax, a Ferengi Salvage Barge drops out of warp in the hex adjacent to the Gygax.  On the next round, if they're not interfered with they'll attempt to capture the Gygax.

If Woz shields are down the Ferengi may attempt to beam a boarding party over to the bridge of the Woz.  These four strongmen have tokens and character sheets in the hidden Black player view.  These Ferengi are not part of the Ferengi Alliance, but they are only NEARLY ruthless; their weapons are on a stun/non-lethal setting.  They want to capture only.  There's profit in hostages, profit in captured goods.  No profit in killing.

The crew of the Gygax are dead, floating around in a ship completely without power or gravity.  It's hundreds below zero inside, so they're all quite stiff, too.  The Ferengi have nothing to do with the failure in the Gygax's power systems.  They're simply opportunists.

Since this star system (like any star system) is in continual motion across the universe, the cause of this disaster is no longer in the area.  It was about a dozen fractures in the space-time continuum, bubbles of different sizes where time moves at a different speeds.  The Gygax's warp core passed through a bubble where time was moving approximately 76.9 million times faster than normal.  From the crew's perspective, the warp core and all emergency reserve power was drained in 2.7 seconds.  Anybody who was in the chamber during that time vanished in a dust cloud, so not all engineering crew's bodies are accounted for (but there's lots of white powder on the floor of the warp core room).    With no power whatsoever, the crew was unable to send a transmission for help or even record a log of what happened.  The ship didn't lose oxygen instantly, but at a natural pace, roughly 20 hours ago.  With outside temperatures being what they are the freeze didn't take long, but the crew's bodies' locations and positions should reflect the 15 minutes of dying time the crew had.

If the crew of the Woz beam to the Gygax before taking care of the Ferengi, the Ferengi will beam over there too and a ground conflict will occur on the Gygax in zero gravity and EV suits.

In any ground conflict situation, the Ferengi may attempt social conflict instead of using their weapons to get the crew to surrender peacefully.  Players can of course 'Succeed at a Cost' should they fail these rolls, or it'd be Game Over.
